children.content: Russia has sent 27 ton of humanitarian aid for civilians in the Gaza Strip to be transported from Egypt, according to their emergency situations ministry.
"A special plane has taken off from the airport at Ramenskoye near Moscow for El-Arish in Egypt," deputy minister Ilya Denisov said.
"The Russian humanitarian aid will be handed over to the Egyptian Red Crescent to be sent to the Gaza Strip,."
He said the aid comprised "wheat, sugar, rice (and) pasta".

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: President Joe Biden swept into wartime Israel for a 7.5-hour visit that produced a heaping dose of vocal support, a deal to get limited humanitarian aid into Gaza from Egypt and a plea for Israelis not to allow rage over the deadly Hamas attack to consume them. "I understand. Many Americans understand," Mr Biden said as he wrapped up his stay in Tel Aviv, He likened the October 7 Hamas attack to the 9/11 terrorist attack in the US that killed nearly 3,000 people in 2001. "You can't look at what has happened here … and not scream out for justice," he said. "But I caution this: While you feel that rage, don't be consumed by it," he said. "After 9/11, we were enraged in the United States. And while we sought justice and got justice, we also made mistakes." He urged Israel to step back from the brink, not just to ease growing tensions in the middle east that threaten to spiral into a broader regional conflict, but also to reassure a world rattled by images of carnage and suffering, in Israel and Gaza alike. Aboard the flight back to Washington Biden spoke by phone with Egyptian President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi who agreed to reopen his country’s sealed border crossing with Gaza and allow up to 20 trucks carrying humanitarian aid supplies to cross. Speaking to reporters aboard Air Force One, Biden said roads near the crossing would first need hours of repairs, but that aid could begin rolling into the region by Friday. AP/ABC
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Biden wraps up 7.5 hour Israel visit with warning against being 'consumed' by rage

children.content: President Joe Biden swept into wartime Israel for a 7.5-hour visit that produced a heaping dose of vocal support, a deal to get limited humanitarian aid into Gaza from Egypt and a plea for Israelis not to allow rage over the deadly Hamas attack to consume them.
"I understand. Many Americans understand," Mr Biden said as he wrapped up his stay in Tel Aviv,
He likened the October 7 Hamas attack to the 9/11 terrorist attack in the US that killed nearly 3,000 people in 2001.
"You can't look at what has happened here … and not scream out for justice," he said.

"But I caution this: While you feel that rage, don't be consumed by it," he said. "After 9/11, we were enraged in the United States. And while we sought justice and got justice, we also made mistakes."

props.alt: An image of Biden wearing a blue zip up fleece while saluting.

children.content: Joe Biden has landed in the US at the Join Base Andrews in Maryland.
(Reuters: Evelyn Hockstein)

He urged Israel to step back from the brink, not just to ease growing tensions in the middle east that threaten to spiral into a broader regional conflict, but also to reassure a world rattled by images of carnage and suffering, in Israel and Gaza alike.

Aboard the flight back to Washington Biden spoke by phone with Egyptian President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi who agreed to reopen his country’s sealed border crossing with Gaza and allow up to 20 trucks carrying humanitarian aid supplies to cross.
Speaking to reporters aboard Air Force One, Biden said roads near the crossing would first need hours of repairs, but that aid could begin rolling into the region by Friday.
AP/ABC
